E-B-S snapshots, encryption, and instance store.

A snapshot is a point-in-time backup of a volume, stored in S3 behind the scenes; AWS manages it, so you don't see the bucket. Snapshots are incremental: the first one copies every used block, and each later one copies only the blocks that changed. A restore creates a new volume in any availability zone of the region, or in another region after you copy the snapshot across; that copy is the standard way to move a volume between zones or regions. There are three extensions. Snapshot Archive is about seventy-five percent cheaper for rarely-restored compliance snapshots, taking twenty-four to seventy-two hours to restore. Recycle Bin holds deleted snapshots for one to three hundred sixty-five days, the fat-finger safety net. And Fast Snapshot Restore pre-warms a snapshot so new volumes have full performance immediately, with no lazy-load latency.

E-B-S encryption is A-E-S-two-fifty-six backed by K-M-S, applied transparently: data at rest, snapshots, and the traffic between the volume and the instance are all encrypted, with the Nitro hardware doing the work, so the overhead is negligible. Snapshots of an encrypted volume are encrypted, and volumes from an encrypted snapshot are encrypted. Flip on account-level default encryption early, and every new volume and snapshot is then encrypted automatically; note that existing volumes aren't retroactively encrypted.

Instance Store is the opposite trade. It's physically-attached N-V-M-e on the host, giving millions of I-O-P-S and sub-millisecond latency, but it's completely ephemeral: stop the instance, terminate it, or lose the host, and the data is gone; only a reboot keeps it. It's included in the instance price, fixed in size, and can't be detached or resized. Use it for caches, M-L scratch space, and replicated distributed systems like Cassandra and Kafka, where node-local data loss is normal and the cluster heals itself.
